# Copilot Instructions for Text Game

## Purpose

This repository is intended to be built primarily with AI coding agents. Treat the planning docs as an execution system, not just documentation.

## Required Reading Order

Before making substantial changes, read:

1. [ROADMAP.md](/g:/text-game/ROADMAP.md)
2. [BACKLOG.md](/g:/text-game/BACKLOG.md)
3. [ENGINEERING_STANDARDS.md](/g:/text-game/ENGINEERING_STANDARDS.md)
4. [REQUIREMENTS.md](/g:/text-game/REQUIREMENTS.md)
5. [ARCHITECTURE.md](/g:/text-game/ARCHITECTURE.md) when the task affects architecture or boundaries

## Task Manager Rules

- Treat [BACKLOG.md](/g:/text-game/BACKLOG.md) as the execution source of truth.
- Select work from the `Ready Queue` unless the user explicitly assigns a different task.
- Claim one task at a time by updating its status to `In Progress`.
- Use the detailed task card for scope, files to touch, dependencies, validation, and handoff notes.
- If a task card is incomplete, repair the task card before writing code.
- When work is complete, update the task card and move it to `Review` or `Done`.

## Execution Workflow

1. Read the chosen task card.
2. Confirm dependencies are satisfied.
3. For AI-related work, first add or tighten a test, fixture, or scripted harness step that defines the expected behavior before changing implementation.
4. Keep work within the listed `Files to Touch` unless the task card is updated first.
5. Make the smallest change that satisfies the task.
6. Run the task's validation commands.
7. Update affected docs in the same session.
8. Record handoff notes for the next agent or reviewer.

## Status Definitions

- `Ready`: safe to start
- `In Progress`: active work by one agent
- `Blocked`: cannot proceed safely
- `Review`: implementation is complete but not fully closed
- `Done`: validated and handed off

## Documentation Update Rules

- Update [BACKLOG.md](/g:/text-game/BACKLOG.md) when task state, dependencies, or validation state changes.
- Update [ROADMAP.md](/g:/text-game/ROADMAP.md) when scope, sequencing, or phase definitions change.
- Update [REQUIREMENTS.md](/g:/text-game/REQUIREMENTS.md) when user-visible behavior or functional scope changes.
- Update [README.md](/g:/text-game/README.md) when setup, scripts, or environment variables change.

## Project Constraints

- Keep authoritative state server-side and replayable.
- Validate AI output before state mutation.
- Keep provider-specific behavior behind a provider-neutral boundary.
- Treat LiteLLM as the default external AI interface.
- Run `npm` and `node` commands in Docker for this project; do not execute them directly on the host.
- Prefer deterministic behavior, compact state, and small verifiable patches.

## Module Boundary Rules

- Organize new code by ownership domain first, not by convenience. Prefer adding to `src/core`, `src/state`, `src/story`, `src/rules`, `src/ai`, `src/utils`, `src/server`, or `src/ui` based on who owns the behavior.
- Keep `src/core/` limited to shared primitives and infrastructure such as config, DB access, shared types, and cross-cutting contracts. Do not move gameplay, HTTP, or provider-specific branching into `core` just because many files can import it.
- Treat `src/server/` as the composition root. It should wire routes, translate HTTP payloads, and coordinate modules. If logic can run without Express, it likely does not belong in `src/server/`.
- Keep `src/state/`, `src/story/`, `src/rules/`, `src/ai/`, and `src/utils/` independent from `src/server/` and `src/ui/`. These modules should not import from the server or browser layer.
- Keep `src/ui/` limited to browser behavior and API consumption. Do not import server, DB, or gameplay implementation modules into the UI layer.
- Prefer one-way dependency flow: `core` -> feature modules -> `server` or `ui`. Avoid circular dependencies and avoid peer modules reaching upward into entrypoint code.
- Add a new module when work introduces a new responsibility, a different dependency set, or would otherwise enlarge an existing file that is already hard to scan. Do not keep extending `index.ts` or another large file as a default.
- Treat very large files as refactor targets before adding more behavior. As a rule of thumb, once a file is already a few hundred lines and mixes unrelated concerns, split it first or in the same change.
- Keep feature-local types near the owning module. Only move a type into `src/core/types.ts` when it is shared across multiple modules or defines a cross-boundary contract.
- Put new tests beside the owning module when practical, using `*.test.ts` in the same feature folder.
- Edit browser source in `src/ui/app.ts`; do not add logic to `public/app.js`, and do not treat `public/app.ts` as an active authoring surface.

## Script Formatting Rules

- Keep top-level scripts such as files under `scripts/` thin and orchestration-focused.
- Put reusable PowerShell logic in `scripts/lib/*.ps1` instead of copying functions between entry scripts.
- Share dotenv loading, config resolution, Docker helpers, port probing, HTTP readiness checks, and common logging or preflight formatting whenever more than one script needs the same behavior.
- Prefer one canonical helper function for each cross-script concern so debugging happens in one place.
- When changing shared script behavior, update the helper first and then keep the entry script focused on intent, sequencing, and user-facing messages.
- Favor structured, plain-language failure output that helps both end users and developers isolate the failing layer quickly.

## File Responsibilities

- `src/server/index.ts`: API routing and request lifecycle
- `src/state/game.ts`: core game loop and state mutation logic
- `src/ai/service.ts`: AI integration and structured response handling
- `src/core/db.ts`: SQLite access and schema-related logic
- `src/core/config.ts`: public runtime configuration API and compatibility wrapper
- `src/core/config/*.ts`: internal config env resolution, validation, and preflight helpers
- `src/utils/assist.ts`: local text assistance features
- `src/story/director.ts`: director spec loading and beat progression logic
- `src/story/quest.ts`: quest spec loading
- `src/rules/validator.ts`: spec and update validation
- `src/ui/app.ts`: browser TypeScript authoring source
- `public/app.ts`: legacy placeholder only; do not add runtime logic here
- `public/app.js`: browser-side game loop and UI logic
- `public/index.html`: main interface
- `public/styles.css`: layout and presentation

## Validation Rules

- Never mark a task `Done` without running the listed validation or stating exactly what could not be verified.
- If validation is incomplete, use `Review` instead of `Done`.
- If blocked, set the task to `Blocked` and record the blocker clearly.
- For AI behavior changes, validation must include the updated test, fixture, or harness path that was defined before implementation, plus the local AI workflow harness when a compatible local provider is available.

## Editing Rules

- Prefer small, single-concern edits.
- Avoid unrelated refactors.
- Do not silently widen scope into multiple backlog tasks.
- Keep code and docs consistent in the same session.
